It is not at all clear that the two parts of this work should be
treated as forming a single book rather than separately. Part i
ends with a verse colophon and blank leaf, and is on different
paper from part ii, the opening words of which, moreover, seem
to allude to it as a separate work. The paper in part i may
intentionally have been made thicker than the rest because it was
more likely to be thumbed, and the words 'superioribus nuper
diebus' with which part ii opens may possibly refer only to the
circulation of this part in manuscript. On the other hand the
92 type in which part ii is printed does not appear again in any
book in the Museum collection till the Constitutions of Clement V,
finished 13 August, 1471, and the use of two pinholes in mid margin
points to a date slightly later still. The type in part i is unusually
heavily printed, and the paper does not appear to have shrunk at
all after being wetted. The measurement of 20 lines of type 118
is thus 2 mm. more than usual.
